<div>Good question Rajat.</div>
<div><br>
</div>
<div>In earlier versions of Linux there was a limit to the amount of memory=
 a user space program could have. Similar to what we see in xv6.</div>
<div><br>
</div>
<div>Since pentium pro however there is a paging mode called PAE which allo=
ws more than 4gb to be addressed.</div>
<div>https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Physical_Address_Extension</div>
<div><br>
</div>
<div>Recent linux kernels use pae to support huge user processes ... in the=
 order of 2^48 bytes...</div>
<div><br>
</div>
<div><br>
</div>
<div>Chester</div>
<div><br>
